If you haven't heard of .460 rowland, you're missing out. Its based off .45 auto, using the same projectiles, and a slightly longer case to prevent chambering in standard 45 firearms. I will be including all my 460 in this sale. 200 rds of Rowland duty loading (230 gr HP) and 350 rounds of Rowland dangerous game loading (250 gr Hardcast). These rounds on 460Rowland.com are over $1 per round before shipping and wait times. title: For Sale:  Winchester M1 Garand DCM Issued RRAD Rebuild-TRADE?
postcontent: For your consideration is my Winchester M1 Garand which I purchased from the DCM in 1981 (original paperwork included with rifle). The rifle was used for M1 Matches at my local gun club, and has always shot well. The rifle receiver was made by Winchester in Dec. of 1940. According to on-line forum information responses, the rifle was rebuilt by the Red River Army Depot in the 1960's, though no markings appear on the receiver legs other than the drawing number. Most parts used during the rebuild were "SA" - Springfield Armory, and the birch stock is lighter than the darker (walnut?) uppers. The rifle always operated well, and was far more accurate than its owner's capabilities. This is a well cared for rifle, with plenty of barrel life left, and never shot corrosive ammo. I really hate to see her go, but she's too pretty to be left in the safe! title: For Sale:  FS: Customized Glock 32, 3rd gen Leupold Deltapoint (included) holsters & more
postcontent: FS: Customized Glock 32, Gen 3,  slide milled for direct mount of Leupold Deltapoint included as shown in pic  (and will fit Deltpoint Pro) with BUIS, (Deltapoint w/7.5 moa delta IS included) plain clothes holster mag pouch/flashlight, range (IDPA USPSA) holster and dual mag pouch; includes original parts that were replaced plus more.  ===(NO INTEREST IN TRADES OR PARTING OUT)=============More pics at https://www.flickr.com/photos/houstonpappas/albums/REDACTED1143755======Lightly used custom setup on Glock 32, Gen 3, 357 Sig. Includes all of the following. Contact to receive extensive pics to verify what you are bidding on/buying and the visual condition of low usage----Glock 32, caliber 357 Sig gen 3 pistol, black; original black case with all usually included items including 2 fired cases. ---All original parts that were replaced.--- 1 glock 22 round magazine,---1 glock 13 round magazine---2 glock 13 round magazines w/Aarendondo +3 round extension and  spring---Slide custom CNC milled for direct mount of Deltapoint & later remilled for Deltapoint Pro w/all 4 registration points for additional stability and close fit; with the Deltapoint pictured, there is a small space f&r to accommodate the latest Deltapoint Pro; see pic--BUIS (back up iron sights) plain rear .150 wide tritium/dot front----rear sight dovetailed in front of MRD so it does not occlude view of delta reticle----additional narrower plain front sight.----.500" tall custom tritium (3-dot) Dawson Precision sights included for BUIS with Deltapoint Pro, when you upgrade----- ghost rocket 3.5lb trigger---TR Graham-The Glocksmith match grade barrel lock for consistent stable lockup of barrel----1 set glock firing pin retaining clips----glock ejector specific for the 357 Sig round---Dale Hunnicuit Grip reductions, Tomball Texas, performed the following work; under cut bottom of trigger guard, reshaped front strap for higher fit, rear strap contoured and straightened,  front strap and rear strap has grip material permanently applied for better grip (like skate tape but does not peel off)----Mitch rosen premium holster, 5JR, full length belt slide (black) for 1 1/4 inch belt----Mitch Rosen premium SOS (speir off-side) for 1 magazine/1 surefire 6p/6z (or similar) flashlight, black for 1 1/4 inch belt----Comp-Tac holster and dual mag pouch. There is also a OEM guide rod and a couple of other parts from a Glock 19.Nice gun, works perfect. Since a lot of shops were milling only Glocks for MRD's when they 1st hit the market several years ago, it gave me the opportunity  to immediately start checking  out the MRD for a duty/carry gun until I found a shop to do my Sig's. Never really got as comfortable with Glock as the Sig 229, so it really is of little use to me. My loss is your good fortune. The Deltapoint is more accommodating for me. Biggest window out there for a direct mount on a pistol, and more importantly rugged and no colorization/distorition from the window and makes downrange view natural and comfortable. Many that wear glasses, and/or have less than crisp view of their iron sights, usually can see the reticle and down range clearly at the same time. Although the slide is milled for longer. taller Deltapoint Pro, a 1st gen Deltapoint is mounted securely due to the registration points; is space to the front and rear of the sight. Practically none of the machine shops want to mill the 4 registration points into the slide for a MRD and only want to do a straight cut. Really need a CNC for that. This one has 4 registration points and I think it provides additional stability. Since it is such a solid fit I do not find a change in the point of impact when removing/re-installing the Pro if desired. ===== When you upgrade to the Deltapoint Pro, it has a flip up battery compartment. I think there are a couple of advantages to having the Deltapoint, or any MRD mounted as far to the rear as possible and the rear iron sight mounted in front of the Deltapoint; More accommodating to plain clothes holster; and note the Mitch Rosen holster has a notch cut into it to fit the rear sight so that in fits normally in the holster; if the MRD was further forward it would create a problem. Just as accommodating to carry w/o a rig inside of the pants/belt; if it was further forward it has a propensity to be unstable. When the rear sight is behind any MRD, it necessairly blocks some of the  view of the reticle. No matter little that is, why do that? Allows you to mount the same way you have trained to align the iron sights, maintain the same muscle memory, but now as you begin to find the iron sights the illuminated reticle over powers the iron sights and you go to that; and if for some reason the reticle is down you will know it as you are already going for aligning the iron sights.  Of course the iron sights (BUIS) co-witness, with the reticle. .==== When the Deltapoint is stationary, no movement, for 5 minutes I think, it shuts down. When it detects movement, just touching it for instance, it turns on. There is a boot to fit over it for protection and to keep it turned off.--Please contact with any questions and for more pics.

The subcompact model of the renowned P30 handgun, P30SK (SubKompact) series has all of the sought-after characteristics of the larger frame P30 and P30L pistols but in a more concealable design. The completely adjustable P30 grip feature - consisting of interchangeable backstraps and lateral grip panels - is replicated in the ultra-compact grip frame of the P30SK. This allows the pistol to be easily modified to fit to any individual user. And like its larger frame counterparts, the P30SK is available in multiple trigger firing modes including HK’s enhanced double action only "Law Enforcement Modification (LEM)." For the P30SK, the LEM trigger is configured with a "light strike V1" setup - requiring approximately 5.4 pounds-force to pull the trigger. Other trigger modes include conventional double action/single action (DA/SA) with a serrated decocking button located on the rear of the frame. The DA/SA mode is available with and without dual ambidextrous manual safeties located on the left and right side of the frame. Other ambidextrous controls include dual slide and magazine release levers. Like all P30 pistols, the P30SK features an automatic hammer safety and firing pin safety. An abbreviated Picatinny rail molded into the front of the frame enables weapon lights, lasers, or other accessories to be easily mounted. All P30SK models have been extensively tested during a three year development process. Despite their small size, P30SK subcompacts have excellent weight and balance making them naturally pointable, easy to control, and accurate to shoot; currently available in 9mm.

title: For Sale:  Webley & Scott Model 1905 Semi-Auto(Blowback) Pistol, 1905 Birmingham Production, .32Acp(7.65mm)
postcontent: Up for sale is a Rare early Webley and Scott .32 Auto Pistol. Designed by factory manager WJ Whiting, the 1905 auto was Webley's first small-bore semi-auto. Featuring a fixed, 3" barrel and 8-round magazine, the 1905 was designed for military and police use, but never adopted by any government agency. Produced for only one year, it was quickly replaced in catalogs by the the 1906-the more recognizable pistol that gained fame as the officially issued sidearm of the three London Police agencies(as well as Scotland Yard). Very rarely seen on the collector's market, this pistol is a unique find for the collector of Webleys, police or British handguns. Condition: Its in a very good with the pistol retaining better than 70% of the original factory finish. Bluing has faded in placed with noticable wear on the high edges from holstering. Carbon spotting and oxidation are evident, with no rust or deep pitting observed. Original hard rubber grips show wear and checkering loss, as well as matching chips on the rear side of both, with the right grip being otherwise fine, and the left grip showing damage and repairs(see pictures). title: For Sale:  Vintage Iver Johnson Top Break "Safety Automatic" 32 SW DA Revolver Stk#A079
postcontent: Late 19th century manufactured Iver Johnson "Safety Automatic" 5 shot dual action top break revolver chambered in 32S&W. Rare 5" barrel. Overall condition is pretty rough, the plating is peeling, there is rust and pitting. Ratchet shows wear and lockup is loose. It does, however, function although I would not recommend firing it without a thorough inspection by a qualified gunsmith. A lot of these early revolvers were designed for black powder cartridges and that shouild be taken into consideration as well. Original owl's head grips are crack free and nice. Bore is shiny but there are many dark areas that are pitted or corroded. Rifling still fairly strong. 1896 patent dates, 5 digit serial number, "Iver Johnson's Arms & Cycle Works Fitchburg Mass USA" stamped on barrel rib. Our stock number A079. Asking $165.00. Willing to ship.
